1 
 
ADHD- originating in the gut? The emergence of a new explanatory model. 
 
Anna M. Sandgren 
Örebro University 
Robert J.M. Brummer 
Örebro University 
 
Author Note 
Anna M. Sandgren, School of Medical Sciences, Örebro University 
Robert J.M. Brummer, School of Medical Sciences, Örebro University 
Correspondence concerning this article should be addressed to Robert J.M. Brummer, 
Department School of Medical Sciences, Örebro University, Örebro, SWEDEN 
Contact: robert.brummer@oru.se 
 
 
  
 
2 
 
Abstract 
The microbiome-gut-brain axis paradigm explains that alterations in the central nervous 
system and behavior may be secondary to functional changes in the gut in general and 
more specifically the enteric nervous system. An unfavorable development of the 
intestinal microbial ecosystem, leading to e.g. a diminished microbial diversity, may 
play a central role. This paper outlines, and describes the theoretical basis of, a novel 
integrative model explaining the etiology and pathogenesis of ADHD in a microbiota-
gut-brain context, taking into account the complexity of the bi-directional signaling 
between the gut and the brain. 
 
Keywords: ADHD, enteric nervous system, autonomic nervous system, microbiome-
gut-brain axis, explanatory model 
  
 
3 
 
 
Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD) is a symptom-based diagnosis with unclear 
etiology, and although several potential biomarkers have been suggested, none has so far 
reached enough evidence for clinical use and recognition (1). Pooled prevalence estimates 
indicate a worldwide prevalence between 5.3% (2) and 7.2% (3), with significant variation in 
estimates across studies. Extensive research on ADHD has been conducted under the currently 
dominating neuropsychiatric paradigm, which neurobiologically conceptualizes the disorder 
as polygenic variations that involve an altered function of dopaminergic, adrenergic, 
serotonergic and cholinergic neurotransmitter systems, alterations in brain structure and 
functional networks, and phenotypic variance influenced by psychosocial factors (4, 5). The 
neuropsychiatric tradition is now challenged by rapidly accumulating evidence of 
microbiome-gut-brain bi-directional interplay, that at present are expanding from preclinical 
research into studies in humans. This emerging paradigm emphasises the environmental 
influence on development and function of the bi-directional (bottom-up and top-down) 
communication between the brain, gut and gut microbiome, and the health implications of this 
interaction (6). As such, the microbiome-gut-brain axis paradigm offers a longed-for 
integrative framework for gene-environmental (GxE) research. 
Meta-analysis of adoption and twin-studies has suggested that genetics may 
explain as much as 71% and 73% of the variance in ADHD core symptoms inattentiveness 
and/or hyperactivity-impulsivity, with larger dominant genetic effects on inattention and  
larger additive effects on hyperactivity (7). There is though strong evidence that these 
symptoms are extremes of continuously varying population traits (8, 9), and not categorical in 
character. Intriguing epigenetic research is also beginning to nuance the picture of ADHD as 
being mainly a genetic condition (10-13). Despite this development GxE models and 
integrative approaches in studies addressing ADHD pathophysiology seem spare, and focus of 
  
 
4 
 
 
 
research interest appears skewed towards CNS and behavioral outcomes. Given the 
neurobiological conceptualization above these outcomes can though be expected to interact 
with peripheral nervous system function; i.e. bottom-up processing. Although substantial 
evidence indicates tonic dysregulation (14-16) or altered autonomic reactivity (14, 17) in 
ADHD, the roots and consequences of autonomic imbalance on symptomatology of the 
disorder remains largely unproblematized in literature, and few studies to date have addressed 
the role of the third autonomic branch, the enteric nervous system (ENS). While the 
microbiome-gut-brain axis in ADHD is so far mainly unexplored, a paradigm transition in 
GxE psychopathology research and Neuroscience is expected (6, 18), that hold potential of 
altering the conceptualization of controlling mechanisms for the disorder. 
An explanatory model evolving from the neuropsychiatric paradigm, needs to 
integrate findings from diverse research fields. In ADHD secondary comorbid 
psychopathology like oppositional defiant disorder (ODD), conduct disorder (CD), mood 
disorders and substance use disorders are common (19). In addition to comorbid diagnoses 
there is a high co-occurrence with learning difficulties and other cognitive impairments, 
emotional problems, motor coordination problems, as well as with adverse health outcomes 
like obesity, behavioral-sleep problems, smoking, an elevated risk of physical injuries (19) 
and atopic eczema (20). The phenotypic variation is thus substantial. 
The microbiome-gut-brain axis paradigm implies that ADHD central nervous 
system and behavioral symptoms may be secondary to enteric nervous system dysfunction or 
dysregulation. If so, metabolic and immunologic function should be evaluated in ADHD 
diagnosis and targeted in treatment as well as prevention. An autonomic dysregulation theory 
of autism has earlier been suggested (21). In analogy to this theory, an autonomic 
dysregulation model of ADHD, involving the enteric branch is hypothesized here, suggesting 
that an imbalanced enteric nervous system, with a less rich and/or diverse gut microbiota early 
  
 
5 
 
 
 
in life, may be a core characteristic of ADHD, that underlie the defining symptoms. As in the 
autonomic dysregulation theory of autism (21) core symptoms may represent a reach for 
homeostasis* through behaviors that in ADHD, inversed to in autism, have a stress-increasing 
”alerting” function, that compensate an imbalanced and plausibly enhanced bottom-up  
relative to top-down signaling of the microbiome-gut-brain axis, that entails cortical 
underarousal. In ADHD the defining symptoms may have a regulatory function for 
maladaptive homeostasis of HPA-axis, metabolic, cardiovascular, gastrointestinal and  
immune system function, that underlie dysregulation of emotional processing and 
exteroceptive (sympathetic influenced) as well as interoceptive (vagal influenced) sensory 
input processing. 
The aim of this theoretical article is to outline and describe the theoretical basis 
of an emerging new explanatory model of ADHD etiology, pathogenesis, pathophysiology 
and morphology, and to frame and initially review hypotheses of phenotypic variation and 
epidemiology within this model. The second aim is to elucidate and emphasize the urge for 
interdisciplinary integrative research specifically addressing enteric nervous system function 
in ADHD. 
Etiology 
 
Hypothesis; A core characteristic of ADHD is an imbalanced, less rich and/or diverse gut 
 
microbiota early in life, influenced by priming, factors affecting microbiota development and 
function (e.g. early microbial exposure, diet, stress, vitamin D status) as well as epigenetic 
regulation of gene expressions. A continuously varying genetic vulnerability can be expected. 
Is there evidence of an altered composition of gut microbiota in ADHD early in 
life? So far most studies discussing implications of the gut microbiome in  
  
 
6 
 
neurodevelopmental disorders are based on preclinical research. The first clinical study, to our 
*The explanatory basis of physiological bio-feedback regulatory networking is debated 
and beyond the scope of this paper. For a theoretical discussion of the evolving concepts 
Homeostasis and Allostasis and their roles in physiological regulation we refer to 22, 23. 
  
 
7 
 
 
 
knowledge, that directly addressed gut microbiota in ADHD has though recently been 
published. In this prospective experimental study 75 infants were randomized for placebo or 
probiotic supplementation prenatally and until they were 6 months old. Gut microbiota was 
analyzed during their first two years and when they were 13 years old. Significantly lower 
prevalence of ADHD and Asperger syndrome were found in the intervention group, as well as 
a significant difference in microbiota composition early in life between affected and healthy 
children (24). If these initial results are replicated the next questions arising regard the origin 
and consequences of the alterations observed. Most likely though, the four major functions of 
the gut microbiome will be affected, and, as a consequence, alterations can be expected in 
microbiome ability to 1, protect from colonization of pathogen bacteria strains; 2, strengthen 
the intestinal barrier and limit the penetration of bacteria and toxic luminal content into the 
body; 3, increase efficiency of nutrient absorption and 4, guide the function and maturation of 
the immune system (25). Additionaly, neuro-endocrine interactions, and the production of 
systemically active compounds, among others short chain fatty acids and signaling 
compounds may be compromized. If the gut microbiota early in life proves altered in ADHD, 
interventions may also be sensitive to timing (26). It is important to note that although most 
attention so far regarding the gut ecosystem has been directed towards its microbial 
composition (microbiome), it comprises also bacteriophages (phageome), viruses (virome), 
fungi and yeasts (mycobiome), which all may contribute to the interaction between the gut 
ecosystem and the host. 
Metabolic function in ADHD 
 
Metabolism has a crucial impact on cellular function and energy homeostasis, 
and perturbations in this bio-energetic system are strongly associated with disease (27). Since 
metabolism is involved in all cellular processes it is highly integrated with other biological 
  
 
8 
 
 
 
systems, a.o. the nervous system. Literature on metabolic function in ADHD has indicated 
increased metabolic activity in ADHD (28), as well in normal BMI-subjects (29), a 
significantly higher prevalence of obesity and/or higher than average BMI-SDS (Body Mass 
Index Standard Deviation Scores) in individuals with ADHD than in control subjects, 
possibly biased by confounding variables, and a high prevalence of ADHD in clinical samples 
 
of patients seeking treatment for obesity (30). An association between ADHD and obesity has 
recently been supported by results of meta-analyses, but the included studies do not permit 
conclusions on causality (31, 32). Maternal pre-pregnancy obesity has, in line with research 
on priming by the maternal microbial flora (33, 34), been associated with an increased risk of 
ADHD symptoms in offspring (OR: 1.89) (35). Also, a consistent association has been 
reported between maternal pre-pregnancy obesity and hyperkinetic disorder-/ ADHD- 
diagnosis or ADHD-medication in children (HR: 1.64), but sibling comparisons suggested 
that the link largely may be attributed to unmeasured familial confounding, although a smaller 
causal effect could not be excluded (36). There seem to be few studies on gastrointestinal 
symptoms in ADHD. Though, an association between ADHD behavioral symptoms and 
colonal problems has been proposed and discussed in the context of a brain-gut axis (37, 38). 
A recent review of comorbidity between ADHD and faecal and/ or urinary incontinence in 
children has emphasized the need of future studies to elucidate the neurobiological 
mechanisms that underlie the association (39). 
If the gut microbiome in ADHD is imbalanced, alterations in metabolic activity 
such as nutrient absorption and waste disposal can be expected. The implicit hypothesis that 
suboptimal nutrition possibly caused by inborn metabolic dysfunction may underlie ADHD 
symptomatology has been addressed in a review of broad-spectrum micronutrient approaches 
as treatment for ADHD symptoms. The evaluation showed preliminary promising results of 
supplementation with medium to large effect sizes, but more research is needed (40). Further 
  
 
9 
 
 
 
evidence from an open-label reversal design study support these findings (41). Metabolism 
depends on access to oxygen, and results in a.o. waste products called oxidants that are 
removed from the body by antioxidative defense mechanisms (42). Preliminary results from a 
meta-analysis of oxidative stress in ADHD suggest normal levels of antioxidant production, 
but insufficient response to oxidative stress and subsequent oxidative damage in ADHD 
subjects (43). This is in line with evidence from a short term follow up study (44). The role of 
the gut microbiome in these metabolic imbalances is unclear. 
Immunologic function in ADHD 
 
The newly discovery of a central nervous system lymphatic system is rewriting 
the possibilities for neuroimmunological interaction (45), and may lead to re-intrepretation of 
immunologic evidence in ADHD literature. So far, immununologic function in ADHD has 
been addressed in several studies. A systematic review of studies on inflammation and 
neuropsychiatric disorders in children and adolescents has shown preliminary evidence of 
elevated pro-inflammatory markers (cytokines) in ADHD (46). Comorbidity as well as 
causality between allergic diseases and ADHD has been suggested, but results have been 
inconsistent. An independent positive relationship between eczema and ADHD and a 
consistent positive association between asthma and ADHD was found in a systematic review 
of epidemiologic studies of the relationship between ADHD and atopic diseases (47). A 
broader association was supported in a nationwide population-based study with age- and 
gender-matched controls, which showed a significantly increased prevalence of allergic 
diseases (asthma, allergic rhinitis, atopic dermatitis and urticaria) in ADHD subjects (OR: 
1.39-1.59) (48). There is also evidence that ADHD behavior symptoms in some subjects are 
food-induced, and the underlying mechanism of this food sensitivity has been suggested to be 
a non-allergic or cell-mediated (i.e. non-IgE, non-IgG mediated) allergic reaction (49). Lower 
odds having ADHD has been associated with a dietary pattern with high intake of kimchi, i.e. 
  
 
10 
 
 
 
probiotic lactic acid fermented vegetables, omega-3 fatty acids, polyunsaturated fatty acids 
(PUFA: s) and low intake of fast food, beverages in a case-controlled korean study of 192 
children 7-12 years old (50). This preliminary association is in line with findings of diet 
influencing microbiota and suggested secondary health outcomes (51). There is a possible 
underlying connection seen in a study conducted on mice, which indicated that a  
Lactobacillus strain isolated from Kimchi may be capable of switching the Th1/Th2 balance 
towards a Th1 immune response and suggested probiotic properties of three additional strains, 
but further research is needed (52). These findings are interesting in the light of a review in 
which a chronic pro-inflammatory immune dysregulation, likely involving a genetic 
predisposition, is suggested to play a role in ADHD etiology (53). 
Are barrier functions reduced in ADHD? 
 
If so, consequences may be extensive. Among other effects increased sensitivity 
to toxic environmental exposure appears plausible. In a review, strong evidence is noted that 
industrial chemicals like toluene, lead, fluoride and methylmercury, are neurodevelopmentally 
toxic and capable of causing permanent brain damage at low levels of exposure during 
sensitive developmental stages (54). Childhood exposure to lead and prenatal exposure to 
organophosphates have been associated with ADHD, although further evaluation is needed 
(55). The ability of chemicals to cross the blood-brain barrier and be transported to the central 
nervous system through the skin barrier, is increasingly used in drug delivery, for example of 
Metylphenidate for ADHD (56, 57). Reduced barrier functions may raise individual  
sensitivity to chemicals, but also to bacterial toxins and food substances like the protein 
gluten, which shows endotoxin-mimicking and thus inflammation-inducing properties (57, 
58). 
In conclusion, initial clinical results indicate an altered composition of gut 
microbiota in ADHD early in life, but more research is needed. Several studies have linked 
  
 
11 
 
 
 
ADHD to altered metabolic and immunologic function, which indirectly suggest that major 
functions of the gut microbiome may be affected. 
Pathogenesis 
 
Hypothesis; ADHD originates and develops from disturbance of microbial metabolism early 
 
in life and subsequent disturbance of among other tryptophan, serotonin, dopamine, 
norepinephrine and GABA metabolism or formation. 
Is microbial metabolism disturbed in ADHD? 
 
Norepinephrine, tryptophan, serotonin, dopamine and GABA are all 
metabolized or formed by enzymes that depend on the coenzyme pyridoxal phosphate (PLP), 
which is the active form of vitamin B6. In a study on tryptophan metabolism through the 
kynurenine pathway, dramatically impaired activity of PLP-dependent enzymes was found in 
children with ADHD (6-11 years old) versus healthy controls, and it was suggested that a 
disturbance of vitamin B6 metabolism is the core biochemical background of ADHD 
symptoms (59). In humans, a significant amount of vitamin B6 is produced by the normal 
microbiota of the large intestine, in a form that is available for absorption (60), although the 
relative contribution to systemic versus local nutritional needs requires further research (61). 
Can a lack of for example vitamin B6 producing gut bacteria in ADHD be an explanatory 
factor of other alterations seen? 
Can an altered GABA metabolism or formation in the CNS have a peripheral origin? 
 
A cross-sectional Magnetic Resonance Spectroscopy (MRS) study has indicated 
reduced cerebral concentration of the CNS main inhibitory neurotransmitter GABA in ADHD 
  
 
12 
 
children versus controls (62). GABA alterations in ADHD were found also in a later MRS 
study, and included developmental effects (63). The GABAergic system shows both short- 
and long-term stress sensitivity, and in response to acute stress rapid and sex-dependent 
alterations of GABAA receptors have been observed in rodents, possibly mediated by 
  
 
13 
 
 
 
neuroactive steroide and neurosteroide hormones (64). GABA levels may differ between 
brain regions, which can contribute to individual variation in ability to filter sensory 
information and select adequate behavioral responses (65). Also, MRS and fMRI findings 
suggest a positive correlation between the concentration of GABA in the insula of healthy 
subjects and neural activity during interoceptive awareness (66). GABA alterations may thus 
affect both sensory-motor behavior and sensitivity to autonomically mediated changes of 
physical states, possibly in a gender-specific manner. 
The amino acid GABA is a common metabolic product of animals, plants and 
microorganisms like lactic acid bacteria, and is available from diet in a wide range of 
traditional foods produced by microbial fermentation (67). Interestingly, results from a study 
on healthy rodents has indicated that emotional behavior and the expression of GABA 
receptors in the brain can be modulated by an ingested probiotic bacteria strain, via the vagus 
nerve (68). It thus seems possible that an altered GABA metabolism or formation in the brain 
may have peripheral roots. 
Can an altered dopamine metabolism or formation in the CNS have a peripheral origin? 
 
The dopamine hypothesis focuses on dysfunction of the dopaminergic system in 
the brain as the main basis of cognitive, emotional and behavioral ADHD symptoms. 
Involvement of this system in ADHD pathophysiology has gained support in animal models, 
genetic-, psychopharmacological- and neuroimaging studies (5). Can these findings be related 
to the composition of gut microbiota early in life? It has been suggested that the microbial 
colonization process affect neural circuits involved in anxiety behavior and motor control by 
modifying the gene expression of neurotransmitters, major signaling pathways and synaptic- 
related proteins (69). Research has shown elevated turnover of monoamines (dopamine, 
norepinephrine and serotonin) in the striatum, and altered expression of anxiety and synaptic 
plasticity-related genes (dopamine receptor genes, brain-derived neurotropic factor gene and 
  
 
14 
 
 
 
nerve growth factor-inducible clone A gene) in brain regions such as the prefrontal cortex, 
striatum, hippocampus and amygdala, in germ-free mice compared to mice with a specific 
pathogen free normal gut microbiota (69). Additional support that the dopamine system in the 
brain may be affected by enteric neurotransmission have been reported in a review of  
evidence that dopamine release in the brain is induced when the gastrointestinal tract is 
stimulated with nutrients (70). This may function as a sensor and regulating system for caloric 
intake independent of flavor and satiety. The authors concluded that dopamine in the CNS is a 
critical mediator between metabolic/hormonal and visceral sensory cues in regulation of 
feeding behavior. Intragastric glucose infusion (to bypass oral perception) has been associated 
with significantly higher levels of striatum dopamine release than infusion with the amino  
acid L-serine. In rodents, blocking of dopamine receptor signaling during high calory (fat) 
infusions has been observed to evoke intake responses as if the infusions had contained fewer 
calories. Also, blocking of dopamine receptors in the striatum of rodents has been linked to 
increased caloric intake (70). 
Can an altered tryptophan, serotonin metabolism or formation in the CNS have a 
peripheral origin? 
A review of neuro-anatomical, clinical-pharmacological and genetic studies has 
suggested that the serotonin system is involved in impulsivity and hyperactivity symptoms in 
ADHD, although the metabolic background of alterations needs to be elucidated (71). 
Serotonin is a key bi-directional neurotransmitter of the microbiome-gut-brain axis (72). It is 
synthesized from the essential amino acid tryptophan, which must be provided by diet and is 
absorbed in the gut under influence of the gut microbiota. Tryptophan can cross the blood- 
brain-barrier for serotonin synthesis in the CNS (72), but most of the serotonin in the body is 
synthesized, stored and released from intestinal cells, and mediate gastrointestinal functions 
like peristalsis, perception of abdominal pain, satiety and nausea (73). In the brain, serotonin 
  
 
15 
 
 
 
affects learning and memory function through modification of a.o. dopaminergic, cholinergic 
and GABAergic neurotransmission (74). Growing evidence indicates that an altered synthesis 
of serotonin can manifest with behavioral effects on emotion, stress response, appetite, 
addiction, sexuality and visceral pain; gastrointestinal (GI) effects on for example motility and 
secretion; as well as with CNS effects regarding motor control, circadian rhythm, body 
temperature, CNS vascular tone and cerebellar regulation (72). Results have suggested that  
the signaling properties of serotonin are altered in response to intestinal inflammation, with 
decreased expression and function of the serotonin-selective reuptake transporter (SERT).  
This leads to increased availability of serotonin both in the gut and in the circulation (73). An 
in vitro study has indicated a decreased transport capacity of tryptophan in boys with 
combined type ADHD, which may imply lower serotonin levels in the CNS (75). 
Tryptophan, although essential for serotonin synthesis, is mainly metabolized 
along the so called “kynurenine pathway”, which is a humoral (anti-body mediated) immune 
route stimulated by inflammation and glucocorticoid hormones (72). Accumulating evidence 
involves the gut microbiota in regulation of metabolism along this pathway (72). When 
tryptophan metabolism along the kynurenine pathway is increased it may reduce the amount 
available for serotonin synthesis, which can lead to GI alterations due to serotonergic 
deficiency (72). Kynurenine that has been converted from tryptophan peripherally can cross 
the blood-brain-barrier and is the dominant source for the CNS (72). Kynurenine has two 
metabolites, that have either neurotoxic or neuroprotective properties, and evidence suggest 
that imbalance between them, with abnormal elevation of the neuroprotective metabolite 
“kynurenic acid; KYNA” can induce cognitive impairment (72). This is interesting in the light 
of preliminary results that suggest lower levels of the potentially neurotoxic metabolite (3HK) 
in children with ADHD versus controls (76). 
  
 
16 
 
 
 
In conclusion, preclinical evidence indicates that gut microbiota may affect 
tryptophan, serotonin, dopamine and GABA metabolism or formation in the brain. Clinical 
studies have reported altered tryptophan, dopamine, GABA and vitamin B6 metabolism in 
ADHD, which suggest that microbial metabolism may be affected, but studies directly 
addressing this question are needed. 
Pathophysiology 
 
Hypothesis; Disordered physiological processes associated with ADHD are maladaptive 
 
homeostasis of HPA-axis, metabolic, cardiovascular, gastrointestinal and immune system 
function. An altered immunoregulation (influenced by a lower/imbalanced microbial exposure 
and an unfavorable gut microbiota development early in life), imbalanced and plausibly 
enhanced bottom-up relative to top-down signaling of the microbiome-gut-brain axis mediate 
symptom manifestation and severity. ADHD symptoms may have a regulatory function. 
Can allostatic accommodation have a peripheral origin? 
 
In the theoretical concept of allostasis an organism is accomodating to a stressor 
by adjusting homeostatic set points to better fit the current environmental circumstances (77). 
These changes are argued to be initiated in the brain (hippocampus, amygdala and pre-frontal 
cortex) and to have secondary peripheral consequenses with activation of the HPA-axis, 
alterations of metabolism, cardiovascular activity, gastrointestinal and immune system 
function (77). If stressors are chronic, it is proposed that the short-term gains of allostatic 
accomodation decreases and that the physiological adaptions become automatic. According to 
this line of thoughts there are stress-sensitive periods in human neurodevelopment that 
manifest as windows of plasticity and vulnerability and result in higher effects of stress- 
  
 
17 
 
exposure, with long-term consequences for physical and mental health (77). Mainly animal 
research (78, 79), but also human studies (80) have shown that early stress exposure can affect 
epigenetic regulation of gene expressions that modify stress responses, and suggested that 
  
 
18 
 
 
 
resulting alterations may be both inherited and reversed. It has been proposed that the 
microbiota may mediate cortical as well as peripheral epigenetic regulation, but more 
interdisciplinary research is needed to elucidate the mechanisms involved (81). Additionaly, it 
has been suggested that microbiota related factors such as early-life nutrition and perinatal 
tactile stimulation from the mother, in interaction with stress hormones and stress-related 
neuropeptides, are involved in epigenetic programming of adult hippocampal structure, 
plasticity and function (82). 
Interventions aiming to adjust the homeostatic equilibrium of the stress-response 
system are suggested to focus on altering the individual experience of the stress process,  
either by reducing stress or stress responses, and time the interventions to periods when the 
neural circuits involved are most plastic to change (77). It has been suggested that modulation 
of enteric microbiota during critical microbial-neural developmental windows, may prevent 
neurodevelopmental deficits and brain disorders later in life (26). Further research is though 
needed to resolve if allostatic accommodation can have peripheral roots. 
What physiological CNS consequences can be expected if afferent enteric signaling is 
dysregulated and plausibly enhanced? 
The enteric nervous system is connected to the sympathetic as well as the 
parasympathetic nervous system (83), and mainly communicates with the brain through the 
vagus nerve (cranial nerve X) and spinal cord pathways (84). Also, 75% of the 
parasympathetic nervous system consists of the vagus nerve (85), with a ratio of 9:1 for 
afferent versus efferent vagal fibres in peripheral nerve bundles (86). An autonomic 
dysregulation model of ADHD that involves enteric imbalance thus implies vagus nerve 
dysregulation. Several studies have reported altered activity and/or reactivity of the 
parasympathetic nervous system in ADHD (15-17, 87, 88), but findings are inconsistent (see 
  
 
19 
 
 
 
overview in (15)). It is also unclear how cortical activation and peripheral arousal in ADHD 
are related, although preliminary data has suggested a possible inverse correlation (89). 
Afferent vagus nerve stimulation may have effects comparable to elevated 
afferent vagal activity caused by enhanced enteric signaling, and can therefore be used as a 
model for evaluation of presumptive physiological CNS consequences. Afferent vagus nerve 
signaling stimulates the HPA-axis releasing glucocorticoid hormones (90). Also, animal 
studies have indicated that stimulation of vagal afferents inhibits parasympathetic efferent 
signaling to the heart, and thus reduces cardiac vagal tone (91, 92). In rodent studies, vagus 
nerve stimulation towards the nucleus of the solitary tract (i.e. afferent vagal activation), 
increased the firing rate of norepinephrine releasing neurons of the locus coeruleus and 
subsequent serotonin releasing neurons of the dorsal raphe nucleus (93). This indicates that 
vagus nerve stimulation support the excitatory pathway to the locus coeruleus more than the 
parallel inhibitory GABAergic pathway (93). A rodent study has also shown that chronic 
peripheral vagus nerve impairment caused by unilateral microchip low-frequency vagus 
stimulation lead to dopamine system inhibition in different brain structures (especially 
mesolimbic and mesocortical systems) (94). Additionally, electrical stimulation of the 
peripheral vagus nerve has resulted in significant alterations of physiologically important 
nutritional macro- and trace elements in dopamine related brain structures (substantia nigra 
and corpus striatum) of rodents (95). This indicates that enhanced afferent enteric signaling,  
as hypothesized here, may compromise metabolic homeostasis in vagus nerve related CNS 
regions. Metabolic alterations linked to vagus nerve activity have been found also in a clinical 
cohort study, showing that vagus nerve stimulation significantly increased energy expenditure 
(96), which has been reported elevated in ADHD subjects (28, 29). It is worth noticing that 
experimental overstimulation of a nerve is known to result in reduced transmission of stimuli 
due to lack of neurotransmitter substance (94). This can be relevant to severe ADHD 
  
 
20 
 
 
 
symptoms, if viewed as continuous traits, and entail paradoxical effects that may cause 
equivocal findings. Neuro-immune modulatory interactions are often non-linear. It therefore 
seems reasonable to assume that vagus nerve dysregulation due to reduced but also enhanced 
enteric signaling may compromize homeostasis of immune system function and inflammatory 
regulation, and increase tryptophan metabolism along the kynurenine pathway. Vagus nerve 
stimulation in conditions with vagal underactivity (97- 99) may thus show positive efficacy 
outcomes that seem contradictory to our hypothesis if they are interpreted as linear 
interactions. It may equally be important whether efferent or afferent vagal stimulation is 
applied (90). Several studies have indicated altered immunological markers and tryptophan 
metabolism in ADHD (46, 75, 76, 100), which support our hypothesis of enteric 
dysregulation. 
Can imbalanced and plausibly enhanced bottom-up relative to top-down signaling of the 
microbiome-gut-brain axis explain attention symptoms in ADHD? 
Inattention, with difficulty organizing and sustaining in activities or tasks, 
distractability and frequent failure to attend details etc. are core symptoms in ADHD 
diagnostic criteria. These attention deficits have been suggested to reflect a low arousal level 
that secondary impair executive and endogenous (but not exogenous) attention orienting 
(101). Also, an integrative theoretical model has suggested that dysregulation between tonic 
and phasic activity of the locus coeruelus norepinephrine arousal system compromises 
attentional performance in ADHD and predispose to impulsive behaviors (102). Can ADHD 
attention symptoms be secondary to increased vagal afferent signaling that bias information 
processing towards bottom-up exogenous attention orienting? 
Afferent vagus nerve fibers project sensory information to the locus coeruleus 
via the nucleus of the solitary tract (93). Evidence has indicated that activation of the locus 
coeruleus is triggered by environmental sensory cues that provoke interruption of ongoing 
  
 
21 
 
 
 
behavior in order to reorientate and facilitate an adaptive behavior response (103). 
Norepinephrine from the locus coeruleus neurons is the only known source of this 
neurotransmitter for a majority of the forebrain (103). Like dopamine, norepinephrine has a 
U-shaped influence on prefrontal cortex cognitive abilities and physiology (104). This means 
that both too high levels (as in acute uncontrollable stress) and too low levels (as in fatigue 
and plausibly hypoarousal) impairs prefrontal cortex function (104). Low tonic arousal in 
normal subjects has been associated with asymmetric visuo-spatial attention, favoring stimuli 
from the right side (105). In the opposite direction, an experimental human study has shown 
that chronic psychosocial stress (i.e. elevated sympathetic activation) increased couplings 
between dorsolateral prefrontal cortex and temporal lobe areas that are involved in visual 
processing, which may have the short-term benefits of favoring a single, salient stimulus 
(106). Also, lower resting heart rate variability has been linked to a more exogenous attention 
orienting, which may impede effective emotion regulation (107). An ERP-study (scalp- 
recorded Event-Related brain Potential) has shown reduced automatic attention to salient 
sound stimuli in young adults (age 18-23) with ADHD (n=21) versus controls (n=18) (108). 
The results indicated that the attention problem in ADHD originates at a lower processing 
level, where inhibition is irrelevant. Authors suggested the locus coeruleus as the most likely 
site of deficit, due to its role in arousal and in regulating amplification of incoming (i.e. 
bottom-up) information (108). These results are supported by EEG recordings of evoked 
Gamma-Band Response (GBR) activity, which indicated increased distractability in ADHD at 
an early level of perception (109). Importantly, no deviation was found during working 
memory encoding and retrieval, suggesting that the attention deficit in ADHD is specific to 
interference susceptibility (109). 
Can symptoms have a regulatory function? 
 
If ADHD symptoms have a regulatory function for maladaptive homeostasis of 
  
 
22 
 
 
 
HPA-axis, metabolic, cardiovascular, gastrointestinal and immune system function, 
behavioral characteristics may aim to increase arousal and novelty, in order to compensate an 
elevated afferent vagal activity that entails cortical underarousal (in analogy to (21)). Lower 
autonomic resting arousal in non-clinical subjects has been associated with higher risk taking 
behavior. Interestingly, risk behavior decreased after physical exercise, suggesting also state 
arousal effects (110). In ADHD, preliminary findings from a systematic review and meta- 
analysis has suggested a moderate to large relieving effect of short-term aerobic exercise on 
core symptoms in children (111). Possible underlying mechanisms may be stress-increasing 
as well as catecholamine enhancing effects of exercise, but implications specific for ADHD 
need further research (112). Can hyperactivity symptoms which result in physical exercise 
have a regulatory function? Evidence from a rodent study has shown that a substance (PGC- 
1a1) that increases in skeletal muscle due to physical exercise enhanced peripheral 
conversion of kynurenine into the metabolite kynurenic acid (KYNA), which does not cross 
the blood-brain barrier (113). This indicated that reduction of kynurenine in the systemic 
circulation, as a result of physical (endurance) training, protected the brain from stress- 
induced neuroinflammatory changes associated with depression (113). If kynurenine levels in 
children with ADHD are elevated as suggested (59), it therefore seems plausible that 
hyperactivity symptoms resulting in physical exercise could have a function of reducing brain 
exposure to kynurenine. Also, it has been argued that excessive food consumption in ADHD 
could be a form of self-medication, since there is evidence that food rich in sugar, salt and fat 
have addictive properties comparable to some drugs of abuse (114). Properties shared include 
activation of mesocorticolimbic pathways and elevation of brain dopamine-levels (114). 
In conclusion, clinical evidence indicates that peripheral arousal affect attention, 
a core symptom in ADHD. Preclinical evidence suggests that vagus nerve stimulation (i.e. 
enhanced vagal afferent signaling) inhibit cardiac parasympathetic (efferent) signaling. Here it 
  
 
23 
 
 
 
is hypothesized that this effect underlies findings of parasympathetic dysregulation in ADHD. 
Preclinical evidence has also shown that afferent vagus stimulation affects the GABA and 
catecholamine systems in the brain, which may imply neurotransmitter imbalance. 
Additionally, preclinical and clinical findings have linked increased afferent vagal activity to 
metabolic alterations, that may compromise CNS metabolic homeostasis. A proposed 
regulatory function of ADHD symptoms can at present not be directly evaluated. 
Morphology 
 
Hypothesis; CNS structural alterations in ADHD are secondary to prolonged abnormal input 
 
from the autonomic nervous system. 
 
Can structural alterations be consequences of chronic autonomic imbalance? 
 
A meta-analysis of structural MRI findings in children with ADHD versus 
controls, has reported area or volume reduction of cerebellar regions (especially the posterior 
inferior vermis), splenium of the corpus callosum, right and total cerebral volume, right 
caudate, prefrontal and other frontal lobe regions, and deep frontal white matter (115). Other 
structural alterations have also been reported (116, 117). Hypofunction of the “cingulo- 
frontal-parietal cognitive-attention network (CFP)”, have strong support to be one of the 
factors contributing to ADHD-symptoms (118). The CFP has been shown to be involved in 
cognition, attention, motor control and motivation/reward processes. Interestingly 
hypofunction of the CFP has been suggested to mirror secondary problems rather than 
primary neuroanatomical abnormalities, which has been attributed to abnormal input from 
connected regions (118). Vagal dysregulation, as hypothesized here, may result in such 
  
 
24 
 
abnormal input, and it has been suggested that chronic enhancement of gut to brain signaling 
possibly can lead to remodeling of linked brain regions (119). Structural changes in prefrontal 
cortex dendrites have been observed in rodents exposed to chronic stress (120). In the light of 
the association between hypo- (fatigue), as well as hyper-catecholamine release (stress) and 
  
 
25 
 
 
 
prefrontal cortex functional impairment (104), it seems possible that also underarousal may 
trigger plastic changes in brain morphology. 
Can structural alterations be secondary to disturbed microbial metabolism early in life 
and subsequent disturbance of among other tryptophan, serotonin metabolism or 
formation? 
Neuroimaging studies have among other linked ADHD to structural cerebellar 
abnormalities with smaller posterior lobules VIII to X, smaller superior vermis, progressively 
smaller right and left inferior posterior lobes as well as signs of cerebellar motor function 
ataxia presenting as postural and gait abnormalities (review by 121). Indications of 
significantly smaller superior vermis volume and progressively smaller total cerebellar  
volume have been found in subjects with worse compared to better outcome ADHD (122). 
Serotonergic fibers are the third main afferent fibers innervating the adult cerebellum, and low 
density of serotonin transporter (SERT) has also been found within the cerebellum (123). 
Serotonin has been proposed to control cerebellar postnatal development in three phases by 
stimulating dendritic growth and synapse formation, hard-wiring neuronal connections and 
stabilizing synapses (123). The human cerebellar development, involving migration, growth 
and maturation of neurons, occurs during the first year after birth (123). In the light of 
peripheral tryptophan as well as kynurenine being able to cross the blood-brain-barrier (72) it 
seems likely that altered microbial metabolism of tryptophan early in life may affect CNS 
development. 
In conclusion, although these results seem to be in line with an autonomic 
dysregulation model of ADHD, further research is needed to evaluate a possible association 
between autonomic function and CNS structural deviations. 
Phenotypic variation 
  
 
26 
 
 
 
Hypothesis: Autonomic dysregulation with enteric and parasympathetic imbalance implying 
 
vagus nerve dysregulation, underlie dysregulation of emotional processing and exteroceptive 
(sympathetic influenced) as well as interoceptive (vagal influenced) sensory input processing 
in ADHD. Heterogeneity in degree of dysregulation mediates the variation in individual 
phenotype. ADHD alterations in stress reactivity, immunoregulation, mode of attention, error 
detection, activity level etc. are secondary to autonomic dysregulation. 
Is there physiological evidence of dysregulated bottom-up processing in ADHD? 
 
Brainstem abnormalities have been reported in children with ADHD, and 
predicted 93% of individual diagnoses, in a neuroimaging study with matched controls (using 
white matter compartment of T1 weighted structural MRI scans, DARTEL, feature selection 
with SVM and leave one out cross-validation) (116). Authors noted that since axonal 
connections between the identified abnormal white matter region and the locus coeruleus, 
ventral tegmental area nuclei and other areas of the brain seem plausible, the results imply a 
possible involvement of catecholamine disconnection or dysregulation in ADHD etiology 
(116). This assumtion is supported by measures of Auditory Brainstem Response, which have 
shown deviations in ADHD subjects versus controls (124). 
Can autonomic dysregulation bias emotional processing? 
 
Variations in parasympathetic reactivity has recently been suggested as an 
explanatory factor of neuropsychological heterogeneity in ADHD (87). Lower resting heart 
rate variability, which inconsistent results have shown in ADHD (88, 125), has been 
associated with a more bottom-up reflexive “stimulus-driven” orienting mode of attention and 
impaired top-down (voluntary mode) visual perception and attention to emotional stimuli 
  
 
27 
 
(107). This may lead to ineffective regulation of negative emotion; i.e. impeded emotion 
regulation (107). It has been suggested that cognitive reappraisal is more effective in 
regulating ”top-down” generated emotions; i.e. emotions deriving from cognitive evaluations 
  
 
28 
 
 
 
of a situation, than ”bottom-up” generated emotions; i.e. emotions provoked by perceptual 
characteristics of a stimulus, that are commonly innate and unaccessible to conscious 
awareness (126). In this experimental study cognitive reappraisal of ”bottom-up” generated 
negative emotion resulted in increased amygdala activation (fMRI), and the reduction of self- 
reported negative emotion following reappraisal, was significantly greater for ”top-down” 
than for ”bottom-up” generated emotions (126). Using reappraisal to decrease ”bottom-up” 
generated negative emotions may thus fuel a response that would otherwise defuse naturally 
after removal of the stimulus (126). While ”bottom-up” generated emotions are substantially 
unconscious, reflexive/instinctive reactions that allow fast behavioral responses, ”top-down” 
generated emotions are mediated by cognitions and therefore more flexible (126, 127). 
In conclusion, following these results it seems plausible that emotional 
processing in ADHD may be skewed towards bottom-up emotion generation. There is clinical 
evidence of structural and functional brainstem alterations in ADHD, that suggest a possible 
bias of sensory input processing. The cause and consequenses of autonomic imbalance on 
ADHD symptomatology seem largely undiscussed in literature, and the role of the enteric 
branch remains unexplored. 
Epidemiology 
 
Hypothesis; In addition to methodological differences between studies life-style factors like 
 
diet, D-vitamin status and urbanization influence the variability in prevalence estimates for 
ADHD. Common life-style factors like stress during pregnancy and early in life, a diet poor in 
traditional fermented foods and nutrition for gut microbiota, increasing environmental 
exposure to neurodevelopmentally toxic industrial chemicals, may act as evolutionary 
developmental driving forces towards an increasing epigenetic gene expression of 
  
 
29 
 
continuously varying population-traits within the extreme standard deviation domain, that is 
termed ADHD. 
  
 
30 
 
 
 
Can epidemiological findings be better understood within the explanatory model of 
ADHD outlined in this paper? 
Among factors influencing microbiota composition, richness and diversity are 
bacterial exposure, diet, physical as well as psychological stress (25, 34, 57, 128, 129) and 
vitamin D status (130). If early microbiota colonization is altered in ADHD compared to in 
normally developing children, epidemiological measures can thus be expected to show life- 
style related heterogeneity. Such heterogeneity might be visible in ADHD prevalence in 
western compared to rural lifestyle societies, populations with high versus low degree of 
urbanization, regions with higher versus lower solar exposure or dietary vitamin D intake etc. 
Systematic reviews and meta-analyses have though suggested that the global variability in 
prevalence estimates of ADHD is unrelated to the geographical location of studies (131, 132), 
although significant associations have also been reported (2, 3). In this debate there is a 
noticeable discussion of a possible selection bias due to a majority of included studies being 
conducted in single towns or regions (3), while other characteristics of the countries than 
continent-based geographical location could not be evaluated in another review (2). 
Interestingly, a substantial geographical variation of ADHD-diagnose distribution in Denmark 
has recently been reported, with significant clustering of low incidence of ADHD diagnoses  
in less populated areas, and clustering of high incidence of diagnoses in densely populated 
areas (133). In line with these findings, a higher incidence of ADHD diagnosis in urban areas 
of Taiwan has been reported (134). 
The relationship between ADHD prevalence and regional variation of 
population vitamin D levels has not been explored so far. However, geographic variation of 
ADHD prevalence has been associated with solar intensity, which explained 34-57% of the 
variance, with lower prevalence in regions with high exposure (135). In Northern climates 
ADHD diagnosis and medication have been reported more common in children born late than 
  
 
31 
 
 
 
early during the year (136-138), which has been attributed to relative immaturity (137, 138) or 
a time-trend effect caused by increased incidence of ADHD-diagnoses over time (139). The 
role of vitamin D in the pathophysiology of ADHD has only recently been evaluated. Cross- 
sectional and case-control studies have reported lower serum vitamin D levels in children with 
ADHD versus controls, and insufficient levels in a larger proportion of ADHD children (140- 
142). While a prospective longitudinal birth cohort study has indicated an inverse linear 
association with decreased risk of developing ADHD-like symptoms in childhood with higher 
maternal plasma vitamin D concentration during pregnancy (143), a prospective long-term 
follow up study showed no association between ADHD and maternal serum vitamin D during 
 
pregnancy (144). Also, a prospective study found no differences in cord blood vitamin D 
concentration at birth between children later diagnosed with ADHD and matched controls 
(145). 
If ADHD traits are continuous in character and epigenetic gene expression of 
clinical symptoms is driven by an unfavorable microbiota development early in life, it may be 
expected that ADHD incidence increase over time in societies where common life-style 
factors disbenefit a healthy microbiota development and function. In line with this 
assumption, the prevalence of reported age-specific ADHD diagnosis in Denmark, Finland 
and Sweden has increased significantly over time (146), a trend also described from other 
countries (134). It is however questioned whether the true prevalence of ADHD is increasing 
(131, 147). 
In conclusion, the hypothesis framed above can at present only be strengthened 
by indirect evidence. Further epidemiological research is thus needed to evaluate if life-style 
measures associated with microbiota development and function modulate the global 
variability of ADHD prevalence estimates. 
  
 
32 
 
General discussion and conclusion 
  
 
33 
 
 
 
The autonomic dysregulation model of ADHD outlined in this paper can at 
present mainly be evaluated with preclinical results and studies in the neuropsychiatric 
tradition. Although contextual reinterpretation of evidence gives preliminary support to this 
emerging new explanatory model, parts of it remain unexplored. Clinical studies based on 
microbiome-gut-brain axis preclinical evidence, and specifically addressing enteric nervous 
system function in ADHD therefore seem crucial. Still, system level approaches integrating 
peripheral and central nervous system parameters in ADHD research are sparse. In the light of 
the rapidly evolving evidence of, and expanded implications for microbiome-gut-brain 
interactions in health and disease, the urge for a paradigm shift towards a holistic view of 
central and peripheral nervous system interplay in cognitive impairment and other brain 
disorders has been emphasized, and interdisciplinary integrative research in this area has been 
encouraged as a future imperative (148). It has been noted that integrative systems physiology 
research needs to approach interconnections between the nervous system, immune system, 
energy homeostasis and the gut microbiome (149). The need to bridge “cultural” differences 
and establish interdisciplinary research cooperation between clinician-scientists specialized on 
higher brain functions and scientists studying microbial ecology, has also been addressed 
(150). 
The microbiome-gut-brain axis paradigm implies that ADHD central nervous 
system and behavioral symptoms may be secondary to enteric nervous system dysfunction or 
dysregulation, where a core feature may be a less rich and/or diverse gut microbiota early in 
life. Clinical awareness of this emerging primary role of autonomic nervous system function 
in ADHD seems crucial, in order to consider the diagnostic relevance of metabolic and 
immunologic symptoms, as well as a suggested regulatory function of symptoms. A yet 
unexplored possible primary pathway is hypothesized here, in which enhanced vagal afferent 
signaling, through compensatory inhibition of cardiac parasympathetic (efferent) signaling 
  
 
34 
 
 
 
may underlie findings of parasympathetic dysregulation in ADHD, and mediate symptom 
manifestation and severity. It seems likely that brain regions directly linked to the autonomic 
nervous system and involved in homeostatic regulation, like the cerebellum, will suffer with 
chronic elevation of gut to brain signaling, and that such prolonged abnormal input, as 
suggested (119), may lead to structural changes. The literature reviewed in this paper  
indicates that increased vagal afferent signaling may underlie neurotransmitter imbalance and 
metabolic alterations in the brain that compromise network function, and plausibly can trigger 
plastic changes of brain morphology. Additionaly, it suggests a possible bias in ADHD 
towards bottom-up emotion generation, and exogenous attention orienting that skew sensory 
input processing. 
Several implications of this new explanatory model may be proposed. If an 
altered immunoregulation, influenced by lower/imbalanced microbial exposure and an 
unfavorable microbiota development early in life, is a controlling mechanism driving 
phenotypic variation in ADHD, any intervention reducing inflammation can be predicted to 
reduce symptoms. The anti-inflammatory explanatory value of stress-reduction, diet and 
probiotics, physical activity and regular exercise, sleep duration and -quality, social skills 
training, behavior management and psycho-educating programs etc. in ADHD treatment may 
then, following this line of reasoning, be a mediator for the effect of interventions. The role of 
pharmacological treatment in ADHD, and peripheral effects of ADHD medication has not 
been addressed in this paper. Both stimulants (methylphenidate and amphetamines) and non- 
stimulant (atomoxetine) drugs used in ADHD treatment are designed to optimize 
catecholamine signaling in the prefrontal cortex (4), and are thus aiming at the CNS. Evidence 
regarding negative effects of pharmaceutical drugs on gut microbiota, immune system 
development and function has been discussed, including elevated levels of inflammation (57). 
If these effects hold true for drugs used in ADHD treatment, increased inflammation, 
  
 
35 
 
 
 
metabolic disturbance as well as disturbance of other gut microbiome functions, may 
accompany the desired effects on neurotransmitters. 
If viewing dysfunctional behavioral accommodation to current environmental 
demands as a mismatch between early calibration of physiological systems and the actual 
context faced, i.e. maladaptive homeostasis and/ or discoordination between homeostatic 
systems, the question arises to what extent this regulatory imbalance can be adjusted by later 
interventions. Preclinical research has shown promising results that targeting the microbiota, 
particularly during critical microbial-neural developmental windows, hold a potential of 
preventing later neurodevelopmental deficits (26), hypothetically by affecting homeostatic 
calibration of HPA-axis, metabolic, cardiovascular, gastrointestinal and immune system 
function and/ or the coordination between these systems. It is though worth noticing, that in 
an environment matching homeostasis in ADHD, the symptoms targeted in treatment may 
give an evolutionary advantage in survival. Controversial as well is the reflection that 
common life-style factors like stress a.o. during pregnancy, a diet poor in traditional 
fermented foods, and nutrition for gut microbiota, increasing environmental exposure to 
neuro-developmentally toxic industrial chemicals may act as evolutionary developmental 
driving forces towards an increasing epigenetic gene expression of continuously varying 
population-traits in the clinical range that is termed ADHD. Further epidemiologic research is 
encouraged to determine if life-style measures associated with microbiota development and 
function, like diet, vitamin D status and urbanization are influencing the variability currently 
seen in prevalence estimates for ADHD. 
The traditional view of the brain regulating the homeostatic processes (149), is 
challenged by evolving explanatory models of physiological regulation (22), as well as the 
rapidly expanding evidence of microbial-gut-brain bi-directional interplay. This implies that a 
new explanatory model of ADHD, as outlined in this paper, is evolving from the 
  
 
36 
 
 
 
neuropsychiatric tradition. Integrating findings from diverse fields of research urge a 
paradigm shift in the conceptualization of ADHD, that would direct the goal of treatment into 
rebalancing of dysregulated physiological systems towards adaptive homeostasis, recognize 
metabolic and immune-system imbalances as capable of driving ADHD symptoms and 
therefore as important targets of treatment. Intervention focus would shift from mainly 
compensating manifest symptoms towards preventive actions, recognizing the importance of 
environmental factors and behavior during pregnancy and early in life as important periods of 
immune-system calibration. Focusing on dysregulation of cognitive, emotional and 
physiological systems as a mediating and driving force of ADHD symptoms and severity, 
thus hold the possibility of embracing the diversity of ADHD phenotype and work as a 
holistic psychobiological approach and frame of conceptualization that upgrade the role of 
autonomic nervous system function. To meet the greater implications of a paradigm shift will 
take guts. 
Limitations 
An extensive review of literature is beyond the reach of this theoretical article. 
The initial eloboration on an emerging new explanatory model of ADHD as outlined in this 
paper therefore provides preliminary results, and comprehensive hypothesis testing requires 
further research. 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
  
 
